      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZY7",
        "path": "internal/trust/pending.go",
        "line": 254,
        "first_comment_body": "validatePendingEntry allows OldSHA to be empty and doesn’t validate TSRaw as RFC3339. Given pending entries are meant to represent “currently trusted SHA” -> “new observed SHA”, OldSHA should likely be required (and both timestamps and SHAs should be strictly validated) to prevent malformed queue entries that later fold/sort incorrectly.",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:31Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZY2",
        "path": "internal/trust/types.go",
        "line": 286,
        "first_comment_body": "ValidateEntry doesn’t currently enforce several spec-required invariants: (1) ts is only checked for non-empty, not RFC3339-parseable; (2) OpPromote should require prev_sha to be a valid 40-hex SHA (it’s “the SHA being replaced”); (3) OpRevoke should require prev_sha as well per the spec’s audit requirement. Without these, malformed logs can be appended and later sorting/compaction can misbehave due to zero TS.",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:29Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYy",
        "path": "internal/trust/store.go",
        "line": 345,
        "first_comment_body": "parseLines currently fails immediately on any JSON unmarshal error. With concurrent appends, a reader can observe a partially-written final line and transiently hit “unexpected end of JSON input”, even if writers use a single Write call. The spec (docs/spec/trust-store-v1.md) calls for retrying fold on io.UnexpectedEOF-like truncation up to a small bound; consider adding a bounded retry when the failure is on the last line / EOF so Fold/List don’t sporadically fail under concurrent syncs.",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:27Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYr",
        "path": "internal/cli/cmd_trust.go",
        "line": 583,
        "first_comment_body": "`trust verify` only checks non-empty and equality, but doesn’t validate that canonical.commit and trusted_sha are well-formed 40-lowercase-hex SHAs. This can let garbage values pass the CI gate as long as they match. Consider using trust.IsSHA40 (or the manifest package’s regex) to enforce format and returning ErrTrustDecisionRequired when either field is malformed.",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:26Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYl",
        "path": "internal/cli/cmd_trust.go",
        "line": null,
        "first_comment_body": "`trust promote` writes PrevSHA from the current folded store state, but it never checks that this matches the pending entry’s OldSHA (the “SHA being replaced”). If the store changed between enqueue and promote (or the pending file is stale), this can record an incorrect prev_sha and violate the trust.jsonl schema contract. Consider requiring state[url].CurrentSHA to equal pending.OldSHA (or using pending.OldSHA as PrevSHA and failing if it conflicts).\n",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:24Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYf",
        "path": "internal/trust/store.go",
        "line": null,
        "first_comment_body": "ErrLocked’s message is specific to compaction (“another compact is in progress”), but the same ErrLocked is also returned by PendingStore.rewrite() when pending.jsonl is locked. This makes the error misleading for pending operations; consider either splitting the error per store/queue or making the message generic (e.g. “trust: store busy, try again”).\n",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:22Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYd",
        "path": "internal/trust/store.go",
        "line": 61,
        "first_comment_body": "Store.Path() is documented as returning an absolute path, but it currently returns whatever was passed to NewStore (which may be relative). Either update the comment to avoid promising “absolute”, or normalize to an absolute path on construction.\n",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:21Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYZ",
        "path": "internal/trust/store.go",
        "line": null,
        "first_comment_body": "The comment claims cross-process append atomicity is bounded by PIPE_BUF, but PIPE_BUF applies to pipes/FIFOs, not regular file appends. If the intent is “each O_APPEND write becomes a contiguous record”, it would be better to describe O_APPEND’s atomic file-offset update (and any filesystem caveats) rather than PIPE_BUF, to avoid giving a false guarantee.\n",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:19Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYY",
        "path": "internal/trust/store.go",
        "line": 274,
        "first_comment_body": "Store.Compact rewrites to a temp file and renames it over the original, but it never fsyncs the temp file before rename (and doesn’t fsync the parent dir after rename). This can lose a successfully-compacted trust.jsonl on crash/power loss, and it also diverges from docs/spec/trust-store-v1.md which explicitly calls for fsync-before-rename. Consider reusing internal/fsroot.Root.StagedWrite semantics (write+Sync+rename+best-effort dir Sync) or at least tmp.Sync() before Close()+Rename(), plus best-effort directory fsync.",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:18Z"
      },
      {
        "thread_id": "PRRT_kwDOSIQ0HM59jZYT",
        "path": "internal/trust/policy.go",
        "line": 165,
        "first_comment_body": "In the KindProceedAutoPromote branch, Decision.TrustedSHA remains set to the previously-effective trust (manifest pin or state.CurrentSHA). Since this decision instructs the caller to append a promote record and proceed with the new SHA, consider setting d.TrustedSHA = in.ResolvedSHA (or clarifying in the Decision field docs that TrustedSHA is always the *pre-decision* value) to avoid callers accidentally proceeding with the stale SHA.\n",
        "last_comment_at": "2026-04-25T03:28:16Z"
      }
    ]
  }
}

